Author: morralexand
Text: @Thinningontop @aguy222 @BritainElects @KantarPublic That's not true either. Sweden isn't a legacy member - only Denmark and the UK had a legal opt-out from the Euro. Sweden (and four other members) has a de facto opt-out by refusing to join the Exchange Rate Mechanism.

Author: morralexand
Text: @Figel_Narage1 @aguy222 @BritainElects @KantarPublic No they don't. There are five EU states (Sweden, Poland, Czech Rep, Hungary and Romania) that have avoided adopting the Euro by not joining the Exchange Rate Mechanism. This means that they don't meet the convergence criteria and therefore can't use the Euro.

Author: The_Educaters
Text:
What are the 8 major currencies?

In general, the 8 most traded currencies are the U.S. dollar (USD), the Canadian dollar (CAD), the euro (EUR), the British pound (GBP), the Swiss franc (CHF), the New Zealand dollar (NZD), the Australian dollar (AUD) and the Japanese yen (JPY).

Author: The_Educaters
Text:
How many international currencies are there?
Well, as you may have guessed from the title, there are 180 current currencies across the world, as recognized by the United Nations. The British pound is the world's oldest currency that's still in use, dating back to the 8th century.

Author: Frances_Coppola
Text: @HodlHead21 @cassandrasprod1 @vitriolwithin @jbencof FYI, the British pound is far older than 313 years. It went on to a bimetallic standard (gold/silver) in 1717, abandoned it briefly around the turn of the century and went on to a gold specie standard in 1821. It came off the gold standard in 1914 and went back on it in 1925.
